    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/equiv-input-params",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "The FDA generic centrifugal blood pump is a canonical reference geometry defined entirely by a published CAD specification; no physical manufactured test article exists against which dimensional or surface-finish equivalency could be assessed. The computational geometry is derived directly from the authoritative CAD file — there is no physical specimen to measure, no manufacturing tolerance stack to characterise, and no as-built deviation to quantify. Consequently, the standard equivalency-of-input-parameters assessment, which requires comparison of computational geometry inputs against a physical test article, cannot be meaningfully applied. This scoping decision is consistent with ASME V&V 40 Section 5.3.2 guidance that factors may be scoped out when the physical basis for the assessment is absent by construction. The scoping is not a gap: because the simulation geometry IS the reference definition, any discrepancy between model inputs and the 'true' geometry is zero by definition. The scoping decision was reviewed and approved by the credibility assessment team lead on 2026-03-14."
    }
